Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: xtifr@netcom.com (Chris Waters)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux, the updated and expanded comparison chart, version 2
Date: Sun, 22 Aug 1993 19:07:38 GMT

In <CC5Int.Ao5@frobozz.sccsi.com> kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown) writes:

>Based on the comments I've received in the mail and on this forum, here's the
>second version of the NT versus Linux comparison chart:


>For Immediate Release: NT versus Linux, a feature comparison
>------------------------------------------------------------

>Feature                     NT                          Linux
>-------                     --                          -----

Another one that might be interesting to mention is # of filesystems
supported.  NT can do three.  I've lost count with Linux.  :-)

>C2 securiy                  yes (see comments)                 no (implementable.  You
>                                                       have the source, right?)

My understanding is that this is extremely questionable.  NT claims to
have met the basic requirements for *applying* for C2 certification. 
However, certification is supposed to take quite a while, and I believe
that a hardware+software combination must be certified, i.e. if you run
NT on your clone, there's no way that you could claim C2.

>bug fix response time      several months, minimum     immediate.  Several
>                                                       weeks at most.

Ha!  As a long-time (though mostly former at this point) Microsoft
customer, I'd say that several months is an *extremely* generous
estimate.  This is, oc, assuming that they ever deign to acknowledge the
bug at all.  Then, there's also the issue of *cost* of bug fixes (since
they usually only come with the next release of the product, for which
you invariably have to pay upgrade charges).

>application availability    limited to DOS, Windows    DOS, Unix (almost all
>                                                       source-available
>                                                       applications)

Otoh, this isn't quite correct.  NT can run OS/2 1.x text-mode
applications.  Both of them.  :-)

Then, of course, there's always this feature:

chance that the product     high (they did it            almost none (source
will be dropped like a hot  before, they'll do           availability means
potato, leaving customers   it again).                   that anyone can
in the lurch, if sales                                   support the product).
don't meet expectations.

And, as far as I know, this one is still true:

Supports *incoming* telnet  no                           yes

And, of course:

development tools           no                           yes
bundled

Script language             very limited                 very powerful
