Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: alovell@kerberos.demon.co.uk (Anthony Lovell)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: Sun, 22 Aug 1993 14:20:32 +0000

Drew Eckhardt (drew@romeo.cs.colorado.edu) wrote:

: In earlier Linux kernels, sbrk() would allways succeed, and memory wasn't
: actually allocated until the sbrk()'d pages were actually touched.  Thus,
: it was possible for processes to allocate more memory than was available,
: and Linux would thrash as it ran out.  Recent Linux kernels use some 
: heuristics to determine how much memory is going to be "really" used, 
: and will cause sbrk()'s to fail when it looks like memory will run out,
: meaning this can't happen.

You're going to confuse them, getting technical in a flame war :)

--

anthony

