From: c@royle.org (Chris Royle)
Subject: A nice linux story
Date: Mon, 23 Aug 1993 11:26:14 GMT

For those of you in need of encouragement, here is a story about me, linux
and the world in general :

I started out with 0.98p4, on a 486SX/25 with 4MB of RAM and a 30MB Linux
partition. I'm now running on the following setup :-

i486 DX2/66
Local bus video
DC600 ISA Cache controller with 450MB of storage (300 for Linux)
Adaptec 1540B with 280MB SCSI II (all for Linux)
16 MB on board RAM
4 MB on the IDE disc controller
Dell Ultrascan 17FS Trinitron monitor
Colorado Tape Drive
Genoa CLGD5426 graphics card (1MB) 
Twincom 144DF modem connecting me to the outside world.
(Ether board on the way :-))
4 Serial ports (3 usable concurrently, on its 4,3,5)

(That machine kicks some serious shit, let me tell you...)

Also connected :-

The old 486 SX25 with 60 MB for linux,
a DX2/50 12MB with 120MB for linux
an old 386 DX 25 w/387 60MB for linux

And it all runs very smoothly (well, it did until pl12, but Linus will be           
helping with that little problem no doubt...)

[Smiles broadly]

Everyone at the client's office where the DX2/50 & 386 are are very impressed
with Linux and considering porting some of their high powered simulators
to it since they get twice the performance on floating point work. (The
simulations can take up to 3 days to run on a DX2/66 machine - written in
fortran, the only major porting hurdle... they don't trust language converters).

Hopefully with more occurrences like this little lot, linux should start to
get a real foothold!

Chris.
-- 
Chris Royle               Cheap mail & news feeds over UUCP from UKP5/mo
Managing Director         Windows / X-Windows code, 386s from UKP540
Objectronix Limited       Desktop publishing
Leeds, UK                 Tel. +44 532 661536     

