From: joe@apache.dtcc.edu (Joe Brown)
Subject: Diamond.FAQ (was: Re: XS3-4.4 for Diamond Stealth 24?)
Date: 22 Aug 1993 16:17:06 -0400

* Adjust your Flames to low, please *

First, I'm working on a Diamond.FAQ.  It will be released very
shortly, so that some of you diamond owners may be albe to get X up
and running in colour yet...  

In article <CC5snD.38v@edefix.han.de> edi@edefix.han.de
(E. v. Pappenheim) writes:
              [E.v.P. self quoted original post deleted]
>Thanks a lot to everybody who sent me help. I received about 20 mails about
>this topic. A summary:
>
>- do not use the Stealth 24, it is 'a little different' around its clockchip
>  and not supported by XS3
>- 1024x768 is the highest resolution with 1 Mb VRAM because XS3 installes a
>  256kb cache in the videoram
>- a recommended card is the Orchid Fahrenheit 1280
>- XFree-2.0 will support the S3 and the Cirrus chipsets

I can't refute these claims, however, I will state that it is
currently possible to get 1024x768x256 color operation out of most of
the Diamond products.  The Viper is excluded, I know is *currently*
*excluded* from this group.  It uses the P9000 chipset, and although
it's not protected by the "trade secrets" which Diaomnd Computers Inc,
holds over the Stealth, and SpeedStar, there is no support for this
product, at this time.

I'm not trying to advocate Diamond purchases. There are no OS/2
drivers, nor are there XFree86 drivers that directly support their
products.  There will probably be NT drivers, before OS/2, but who
knows (my guess).

Unfortunatly, many of use Linux users own Diamond products, and I for
one wasted a weekend, trying to get mine to work.  That's why I'm
working on the FAQ.

Okay, I'm happy... I stated my case, and my opinions...
Much of what I said is just that -- my opinion, and I reserve the
right to be dead wrong...

* flame on *
-- 
                Religion:  Yes, I believe there is a Church
         Murphy's Paradox:  doing it the hard way is always easier
(: Joe Brown :)                                         joe@apache.dtcc.edu

